<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-457-163  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 457 163.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  August 30 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>UK: computer misuse outlawed under new legislation. (ComputerMisuse Act)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gold, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Great Britain. Computer Misuse Act 1990 (interpretation andconstruction).andO;Topic:     LegislationComputer hackersComputer crimesLegal IssuesUnited Kingdom.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>UK: COMPUTER MISUSE OUTLAWED UNDER NEW LEGISLATION LONDON, ENGLAND, 1990 AUG30 (NB) -- Starting August 30, computer hacking becomes a specific offence asthe Computer Misuse Act comes into force.andP;  The Act makes it an offence togain access to or modify computer data without authority.andM;Although the UK media has reported that the Act is aimed at online hackers --modem users who gain unauthorized access to online systems -- the legislationalso applies toward computer users who create or deliberately pass on virusor logic bomb programs.andM;Under the Act, penalties of up to six months in jail or fines of up to UKP2,000 can be imposed for the basic crime of computer misuse, increased tofive years and/or unlimited fines in aggravated cases, if programs or dataare deleted or modified or if the offence forms part of a more serious crime.andM;According to a report in the London Times, Michael Colvin, the member ofParliament who sponsored the Act on its passage through the UK Government,the legislation will hopefully act as a deterrent to anyone consideringmisuse of computers.andM;&quot;The new law has the teeth to allow those who persist in misusing computersto be effectively punished, and it will send out a clear signal to computerusers of all ages that misuse is no longer to be tolerated by society,&quot; he isquoted as saying.andM;Although the Act has been welcomed by many in the business community, severalindustry figures, including computer experts on the security and legal side,have expressed concern that the Act is very much in the 'sledgehammer tocrack a nut' syndrome.andM;(Steve Gold/1990830)</TEXT></DOC>